{"step_index":48,"source":"MODEL","type":"VIEW_FILE","status":"DONE","created_at":"2026-07-18T06:43:58Z","content":"Created At: 2026-07-18T13:43:58+07:00\nCompleted At: 2026-07-18T13:43:58+07:00\nFile Path: `file:///home/hieu/Downloads/Code/VAIC%202026/v-nexus/gateway/Dockerfile`\nTotal Lines: 14\nTotal Bytes: 406\nShowing lines 1 to 14\nThe following code has been modified to include a line number before every line, in the format: <line_number>: <original_line>. Please note that any changes targeting the original code should remove the line number, colon, and leading space.\n1: FROM python:3.11-slim\n2: WORKDIR /app\n3: COPY gateway/requirements.txt ./requirements.txt\n4: RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --default-timeout=300 --retries=5 -r requirements.txt\n5: COPY agent/ ./agent/\n6: COPY tools/ ./tools/\n7: COPY domain/ ./domain/\n8: COPY db/ ./db/\n9: COPY docs/data/ ./docs/data/\n10: COPY gateway/app/ ./app/\n11: ENV PYTHONPATH=/app\n12: EXPOSE 8000\n13: CMD [\"uvicorn\", \"app.main:app\", \"--host\", \"0.0.0.0\", \"--port\", \"8000\"]\n14: \nThe above content shows the entire, complete file contents of the requested file.\n"}
{"step_index":49,"source":"MODEL","type":"PLANNER_RESPONSE","status":"DONE","created_at":"2026-07-18T06:43:58Z","thinking":"**Locating Test Files**\n\nI'm currently trying to pinpoint the location of the test files. It seems they're not in the `gateway/Dockerfile`. Now, I'm checking the `gateway/` directory itself, and also seeing if the tests are runnable via `python -m pytest` in a local Python environment. I have a hunch that the relevant files might be in the `/home/hieu/Downloads/Code/VAIC 2026` directory.\n\n\n**Designing Test Instructions**\n\nI'm now designing a `testing_guide.md` artifact to assist with offline and prompt optimization testing. I'll cover offline mode configuration with pre-designed templates via Swagger UI and local Ollama setup.  I'll also detail testing with the Qwen model after setting `LLM_MODE=ollama` and pulling the model, also pointing out where the system prompts reside for prompt optimization testing. I'm focusing on making the process as streamlined as possible, particularly the offline testing.\n\n\n**Refining Prompt Optimization Techniques**\n\nI'm now focusing on how to translate the optimization strategies from `prompt.md` and `offline.md` into actionable steps for the adapter/planner agent.  I'm detailing the process of applying techniques such as low temperature settings, simplifying structured output, implementing validation logic, and splitting prompts. I'm also including concise instructions for rebuilding the gateway container to rapidly test prompt changes using `docker compose build gateway && docker compose up -d --force-recreate gateway`, and *optionally* adding volume mounts to `docker-compose.yml` for real-time development feedback. Finally, I'll explain testing prompt outputs, with instructions on using `curl` or Swagger UI to inspect JSON responses, as well as the importance of the validation step, which uses `_post_validate` within `tools/plan_tool.py` for local model safety. I'll write all this to `/home/hieu/.gemini/antigravity-cli/brain/71e25571-7166-4225-8338-32b4e3317b15/testing_guide.md`.\n\n\n","tool_calls":[{"name":"write_to_file","args":{"ArtifactMetadata":"{\"RequestFeedback\":false,\"Summary\":\"A detailed guide on how to test prompt optimization and offline testing for the V-Nexus system using Docker Compose. It details local LLM setups (Ollama), offline fallback verification, live code reloading, and validation testing.\",\"UserFacing\":true}","CodeContent":"\"# Prompt Optimization & Offline Testing in Docker\\n\\nThis guide explains how to use Docker to test two critical architectural requirements:\\n1. **Offline Testing** (simulating zero-network connectivity using local LLMs via Ollama or static templates).\\n2. **Prompt Optimization** (editing prompts, rebuilding containers, and testing local model output quality).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 🔌 Part 1: Offline Testing Configurations\\n\\nYou can test the system's resilience to offline scenarios in two different ways. Open your [.env](file:///home/hieu/Downloads/Code/VAIC%202026/v-nexus/.env) file to configure the modes.\\n\\n### Mode A: Static Template Fallback (No LLM API)\\nThis mode tests how the system behaves when LLM access is completely disabled (useful as a last-resort fallback or to save API credits/CPU).\\n\\n1. In `.env`, change:\\n   ```env\\n   LLM_MODE=offline\\n   ```\\n2. Recreate the gateway container:\\n   ```bash\\n   docker compose up -d --force-recreate gateway\\n   ```\\n3. **Expected Behavior**: When triggering a learning path/plan request via the frontend or API, the system will bypass all LLM API calls and instantly respond with the predefined offline fallback templates located in [tools/plan_tool.py](file:///home/hieu/Downloads/Code/VAIC%202026/v-nexus/tools/plan_tool.py).\\n\\n### Mode B: Fully Offline Local LLM (Ollama)\\nThis mode lets you run the prompt pipeline entirely on your local machine using an open-source model like Qwen3.\\n\\n1. In `.env`, change:\\n   ```env\\n   LLM_MODE=ollama\\n   OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen3:1.7b  # Or qwen3:8b if your system has >8GB RAM\\n   ```\\n2. Start the services (standard or lite mode depending on CPU/GPU):\\n   ```bash\\n   # Lite mode (CPU-only, memory capped to 2GB)\\n   docker compose -f docker-compose.lite.yml up -d --build\\n   ```\\n3. Download the model inside the Ollama container:\\n   ```bash\\n   docker compose exec ollama ollama pull qwen3:1.7b\\n   ```\\n4. **Offline validation**: You can now safely unplug your internet connection. All chat requests and prompt responses will be computed loc\n<truncated 3358 bytes>","Description":"\"Create testing guide artifact for V-Nexus prompt optimization and offline testing using Docker\"","Overwrite":"true","TargetFile":"\"/home/hieu/.gemini/antigravity-cli/brain/71e25571-7166-4225-8338-32b4e3317b15/testing_guide.md\"","toolAction":"\"Creating testing guide artifact\"","toolSummary":"\"Create testing guide artifact\""}}],"truncated_fields":["tool_calls"]}
